🔍 How to Find Your Files:

For PDF Files:

  1. Windows Search: Press Windows Key + S and type: *.pdf then sort by "Date modified"

  2. File Explorer: Open File Explorer → Go to your Documents or Downloads folder → Search *.pdf → Sort by "Date modified"

For Recent Notepad Files:

  1. Notepad Recent Files: Open Notepad → File → Open → Look in "Recent Places"

  2. Windows Recent Files: Press Windows Key + E → Quick access → "Recent files"

  3. Search for .txt files: Search *.txt and sort by date

For Printed Documents:

  1. Print History: Windows → Settings → Devices → Printers & scanners → Select printer → "Open queue" → See print history

  2. Recent Documents: File Explorer → Quick access → Recent files

📁 Common Locations to Check:

  • Desktop

  • Documents folder

USE POWER SHELL

Here are PowerShell commands to find your recent files:

🔍 FIND RECENT PDF FILES

powershell
# Find PDF files modified in last 30 days
Get-ChildItem -Path C:\ -Include "*.pdf" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | 
Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-30)} |
Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending |
Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime, Length |
Format-Table -AutoSize

📄 FIND RECENT TEXT/NOTEPAD FILES

powershell
# Find TXT files modified recently
Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME -Include "*.txt", "*.log" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-7)} |
Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending |
Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime |
Format-Table -AutoSize

🖨 FIND RECENTLY PRINTED DOCUMENTS

powershell
# Check print spooler for recent jobs
Get-WinEvent -LogName "Microsoft-Windows-PrintService/Operational" -MaxEvents 20 |
Where-Object {$_.TimeCreated -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-1)} |
Select-Object TimeCreated, Id, LevelDisplayName, Message |
Format-Table -Wrap

📂 SEARCH SPECIFIC FOLDERS

powershell
# Search common locations
$Folders = @("$HOME\Documents", "$HOME\Downloads", "$HOME\Desktop", "$HOME\OneDrive")
foreach ($folder in $Folders) {
    if (Test-Path $folder) {
        Write-Host "Searching: $folder" -ForegroundColor Yellow
        Get-ChildItem -Path $folder -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
        Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-14)} |
        Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime, Length
    }
}

🔥 QUICK SEARCH FOR FRANCESCO FILES

powershell
# Search for files containing "Francesco" or "Longo"
Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt", "*.doc*" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Where-Object {$_.Name -like "*Francesco*" -or $_.Name -like "*Longo*" -or $_.Name -like "*Settlement*"} |
Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime, Length |
Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending

💾 EXPORT RESULTS TO FILE

powershell
# Export search results to a file
Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-30)} |
Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime, Length |
Export-Csv -Path "$HOME\Desktop\RecentFiles.csv" -NoTypeInformation

Write-Host "Results exported to Desktop\RecentFiles.csv" -ForegroundColor Green

🚀 RUN THIS QUICK SCAN FIRST

powershell
# Quick scan of most likely locations
Write-Host "=== SCANNING FOR RECENT FRANCESCO FILES ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan

$RecentFiles = Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME\* -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt", "*.doc*" -File -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-7)} |
Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending

$RecentFiles | Select-Object Name, Directory, LastWriteTime, @{Name="Size(MB)";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1MB,2)}} |
Format-Table -AutoSize

powershell
# Search entire C drive for those specific files
Write-Host "=== DEEP SEARCH FOR YOUR FILES ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan

$FileNames = @(
    "*GRAND FINAL*",
    "*210 BILLION*", 
    "*SURPRISE IQ*",
    "*UNBIAS AI*",
    "*BUILDING SETTLEMEN*",
    "*FIRST FINAL*",
    "*Francesco*",
    "*Longo*",
    "*Settlement*"
)

foreach ($pattern in $FileNames) {
    Write-Host "Searching for: $pattern" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Get-ChildItem -Path C:\ -Name "*$pattern*" -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt", "*.doc*" |
    Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime
}

📂 CHECK SPECIFIC LOCATIONS

powershell
# Check common save locations
$Locations = @(
    "$HOME\Desktop",
    "$HOME\Documents",
    "$HOME\Downloads", 
    "$HOME\OneDrive",
    "$HOME\AppData\Local\Temp",
    "C:\Temp"
)

foreach ($location in $Locations) {
    if (Test-Path $location) {
        Write-Host "=== Searching: $location ===" -ForegroundColor Green
        Get-ChildItem -Path $location -Recurse -Include "*.pdf", "*.txt" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
        Where-Object {$_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-3)} |
        Select-Name, FullName, LastWriteTime, Length
    }
}

🗂 CHECK RECENTLY ACCESSED FILES

powershell
# Check recent files from registry
Write-Host "=== RECENTLY ACCESSED FILES ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan

Get-ItemProperty "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\RecentDocs\.pdf" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
ForEach-Object { $_.PSObject.Properties | Where-Object {$_.Value -like "*.pdf"} | Select-Object Value }

Get-ItemProperty "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\RecentDocs\.txt" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
ForEach-Object { $_.PSObject.Properties | Where-Object {$_.Value -like "*.txt"} | Select-Object Value }

# Just show me PDFs and TXTs on desktop and documents

# Check if files were accidentally deleted

$rb = $shell.NameSpace(0xa)

} catch {
    Write-Host "Outlook not accessible - use Gmail export method above" -ForegroundColor Red
}

Francesco Longo Case #21-845 --- ### SECTION 1: REQUESTER INFORMATION **Name:** Francesco Longo **Case Reference:** R. v. Francesco Longo Case #21-845 **Request Date:** October 31, 2025 **Legal Basis:** Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FIPPA), R.S.O. 1990, c. F.31 (Ontario); Access to Information Act, R.S.C. 1985, c. A-1 (Federal) **Status:** Self-represented litigant and subject of records requested --- ### SECTION 2: REQUEST PURPOSE This request seeks all records, communications, and documentation evidencing coordination between government officials, Crown attorneys, police officers, judicial staff, and administrative agencies regarding R. v. Francesco Longo Case #21-845 from May 2021 to October 2025. The request supports investigation of systematic Charter violations, ongoing federal crimes (Criminal Code ss. 342.1, 139, 430), and preparation for civil litigation involving institutional complicity damages estimated at $19.7M-$31.4M based on Supreme Court precedents. --- ### SECTION 3: SPECIFIC RECORDS REQUESTED #### A. powershell
# Search for actual police file numbers in your documents
Write-Host "=== HUNTING FOR REAL POLICE FILE NUMBER ===" -ForegroundColor Red

# Search for common police file formats
$PolicePatterns = @(
    "WR-\d{4}-\d+",
    "WR\d{6}",
    "\d{2}-\d{5}",
    "\d{6}",
    "Occurrence \d+",
    "Case \d+",
    "File \d+"
)

# Check your police disclosure documents specifically
$PoliceFiles = Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME -Recurse -Include "*disclosure*", "*police*", "*occurrence*" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

foreach ($file in $PoliceFiles) {
    Write-Host "Checking police file: $($file.Name)" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    try {
        $content = Get-Content $file.FullName -Raw -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
        foreach ($pattern in $PolicePatterns) {
            if ($content -match $pattern) {
                Write-Host "🚨 POSSIBLE POLICE NUMBER: $($matches[0]) in $($file.Name)" -ForegroundColor Green
            }
        }
    } catch {
        # Skip files we can't read
    }
}

# Also check file names for numbers
Write-Host "=== CHECKING FILENAMES FOR POLICE NUMBERS ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan

Get-ChildItem -Path $HOME -Recurse -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | 
Where-Object { $_.Name -match "WR-\d" -or $_.Name -match "\d{2}-\d{5}" -or $_.Name -match "occurrence" -or $_.Name -match "police" } |
ForEach-Object {
    Write-Host "Possible police file: $($_.Name)" -ForegroundColor White
}

🎯 QUICK CHECK - LOOK FOR THESE FORMATS:

Common Windsor Police File Formats:

  • WR-2021-XXXXX (WR = Windsor, 2021 = year, XXXXX = case number)

  • 21-XXXXX (21 = year 2021, XXXXX = case number)

  • Occurrence XXXXXX

  • Case #XXXXX

# Check your known police-related files
Write-Host "=== CHECKING YOUR KNOWN POLICE DOCUMENTS ===" -ForegroundColor Magenta

$KnownPoliceFiles = @(
    "Item_08_Gratton_Dual_Police_Disclosures.pdf",
    "PoliceDisclosureForensics_20251022-193130.txt",
    "OPP_FRAUD_REPORT_20251012_191045.txt",
    "DISCLOSURE FORM.pdf",
    "original disclosure email sha256.txt"
)

foreach ($file in $KnownPoliceFiles) {
    $fullPath = "C:\Users\User\$file"
    if (Test-Path $fullPath) {
        Write-Host "Checking: $file" -ForegroundColor White
        try {
            if ($file -like "*.txt") {
                $content = Get-Content $fullPath -Raw
                if ($content -match "(WR-\d{4}-\d+|21-\d{5}|\d{2}-\d{5})") {
                    Write-Host "🚨 POLICE NUMBER FOUND: $($matches[0])" -ForegroundColor Green
                }
            }
        } catch {
            Write-Host "Could not read: $file" -ForegroundColor Red
        }
    }
}

$DocumentsWith6243850 = @()

    try {
        $content = Get-Content $_.FullName -Raw -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
        if ($content -match "62-43850") {
            $DocumentsWith6243850 += [PSCustomObject]@{
                Document = $_.Name
                Path = $_.Directory
                LastWrite = $_.LastWriteTime
            }
            Write-Host "🚨 62-43850 FOUND IN: $($_.Name)" -ForegroundColor Yellow
        }
    } catch { }
}

Write-Host "Number of documents containing 62-43850: $($DocumentsWith6243850.Count)" -ForegroundColor White

if ($DocumentsWith6243850.Count -gt 1) {
